FizzBuzz implementation constraints and validation patterns
- Input validation:
  - Ensure input is numeric and integer: Number.isInteger(n) === true
  - If function accepts a start and end range, validate start and end are integers and start <= end; throw RangeError("message") on invalid range
  - Guard against non-finite values: Number.isFinite(n) can be used
- Divisibility checks:
  - Evaluate both-conditions first: if (n % 3 === 0 && n % 5 === 0) => FizzBuzz
  - Then test n % 3 === 0 => Fizz
  - Then test n % 5 === 0 => Buzz
- Edge cases:
  - Zero: 0 is divisible by any non-zero integer (0 % k === 0) so FizzBuzz rules will apply (0 -> FizzBuzz)
  - Negative numbers: modulo semantics keep sign of dividend; divisibility checks using === 0 still work for negative multiples
  - Large numbers: floating point precision may cause Number.isInteger to misreport integers near Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER; avoid relying on integers beyond safe integer range or use BigInt alternatives

2. SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS

Implementation specifications and examples (compact form)
- Function signature (recommended): function fizzbuzzRange(start, end) -> Array<string>
- Input requirements:
  - start: integer (Number.isInteger(start) === true)
  - end: integer (Number.isInteger(end) === true)
  - start <= end; otherwise throw RangeError("start must be <= end")
- Algorithm:
  - Allocate result array of length end - start + 1
  - For i from start to end inclusive:
    - if i % 3 === 0 && i % 5 === 0 push "FizzBuzz"
    - else if i % 3 === 0 push "Fizz"
    - else if i % 5 === 0 push "Buzz"
    - else push String(i)
- Testing pattern:
  - Unit tests: assert fizzbuzzRange(1, 15)[14] === "FizzBuzz" and sample positions for Fizz and Buzz
  - Boundary tests: start === end, negative ranges, zero in range, invalid ranges cause RangeError

3. REFERENCE DETAILS (API signatures, configuration options, exact patterns)

JavaScript language and runtime APIs
- Number.isInteger(value) : any -> boolean
  - Returns true only for Number primitives that are integers
- Number.isFinite(value) : any -> boolean
  - Returns true for finite number primitives
- Remainder operator: a % b
  - Semantic definition: a % b = a - Math.trunc(a / b) * b
  - Use for exact divisibility by comparing to 0 with strict equality
- RangeError(message?: string) : constructor -> RangeError
  - Use: throw new RangeError("message")

Node.js ESM configuration
- package.json "type" field
  - "type": "module" -> interpret .js files as ES modules
  - Absence or "commonjs" -> .js interpreted as CommonJS
- Mandatory file extensions for import specifiers
  - import x from './mod.js' is required; ./mod without .js will not resolve as ESM
- CLI flags
  - node --input-type=module -p "..." for evaluating module code

Vitest configuration and commands
- CLI: vitest --run <pattern> to run tests once without watch
- Programmatic import: import { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest'
- Common assertions and matchers: toBe, toEqual, toMatchSnapshot, toThrow
- Use Vite config for module resolution when tests reuse project build configuration

Best practices and implementation examples
- Always validate inputs with Number.isInteger and Number.isFinite before modulo operations
- Check combined divisibility first (3 and 5) to avoid incorrect outputs
- Throw RangeError for invalid numeric ranges with clear messages
- Use ESM consistent project configuration: set package.json "type": "module" if source files use import/export with .js extensions
- Write unit tests covering typical positions and boundaries; use vitest --run in CI scripts

Troubleshooting procedures
- If import fails with ERR_MODULE_NOT_FOUND: ensure relative import includes file extension and package.json "type": "module" is set if using .js modules
- If modulo results unexpected for very large integers: verify Number.isInteger and avoid numbers above Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER; consider BigInt if integers above safe range required
- If tests fail to run under Node: ensure vitest version supports Node engine; run npm ci then npm test; ensure package.json test script maps to vitest --run pattern

